            <p>Jewish Theological Seminary<lb/>
                736 Lexington Avenue<lb/>
                New York April 17. 5653<lb/></p>
            <p>To Rev Dr. Sabato Morais.<lb/></p>
            <p>The undersigned Trustees<lb/> of the Jewish Theological Seminary Association beg here&#45;<lb/>with to tender unto you their heartfelt congratulations<lb/> upon the happy completion of that span of your life&#44;<lb/> the three score years and ten&#44; which when filled with<lb/> honor and good works as in your case&#44; denotes a ven&#45;<lb/>erable career well rounded out.&#44; To you however with<lb/> your high sense of duty it denotes no cessation of<lb/> activity&#44; and with the continuation of your physical<lb/> force&#44; we may yet hopefully look forward to the years<lb/> to come for the beneficial finits&#91;&#63;&#93; of your zeal as a<lb/> laborer in behalf of the weal of Judaism&#44; and more<lb/> especially do we hope that your eyes will be gladdened<lb/> with the sight of the fair blossoming forth into healthy&#44;<lb/> lusty manhood&#44; of this child of your old age&#44; The<lb/> Jewish Theological Seminary&#44; the fears of infancy out&#45;<lb/>grown&#44; the anxieties of youth outlived and the fond<lb/> dreams that clustered about its birth and growth be&#45;<lb/>ginning to be realized in bounteous measure and<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>without the loss of an illusion.&#44; on this joyous but<lb/> not the less solemn occasion&#44; we of the Board of<lb/> Trustees once again pledge ourselves to render unto you aid<lb/> according to our several capacities and powers in carrying<lb/> on the sacred work which you have undertaken for the<lb/> perpetuation of that Historical Judaism of which you<lb/> are the leading exponent in this Country.  Even though<lb/> we are confident that you will appreciate the<lb/> warmth of our feelings for you&#44; the sincerity of our<lb/> wishes for your welfare and happiness&#44; we are loath<lb/> to allow this momentous event in your life to pass<lb/> without some more enduring expression of our senti&#45;<lb/>ments towards you.  It has therefore been resolved<lb/> to begin on your seventieth birthday the gathering of<lb/> means for the foundation at the seminary<lb/> of the Morais Library&#44; which we hope<lb/> will become so valuable and important<lb/> a collection of works in Hebrew Litera&#45;<lb/>ture as to comport <sic>withe</sic> the dignity of<lb/> <del>of</del> the seminary&#58; to furnish the students of the<lb/> Seminary with the material necessary to equip them<lb/> worthily for the cause they are to represent and the work they are to<lb/> do&#59; to constitute in the centre of Hebrew learning<lb/> and research in America and to indissolubly<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>connect your name with the institution which<lb/> you have founded&#44; for time immemorial&#44;<lb/> Once again uttering our felicitations we pray<lb/> that you may be spared for many years in<lb/> the enjoyment of health&#44; peace and well being<lb/> Joseph Blumenthal<lb/> President<lb/></p>
                
